1 Learning objectives

  1. You can name and explain the characteristics of the two main types of data visualisation.

  2. You can distinguish between data exploration figure and a data presentation figure.

  3. You can recall and explain the four key ways in which the two types are fundamentally different.

2 The two types of data visualisation

Data visualisation has two main purposes: exploring the data during the analysis process and presenting the data to an external audience.

Letâs start by defining our terms:

  • Data exploration means the deep-dive analysis of data in search of new insights.

  • Data presentation means the delivery of data insights to an audience in a form that makes clear the implications.

Exploration visualisations help us develop insights about the structure of the data and get an understanding of the patterns in our data â such as the presence of outliers, distributions of individual variables, and relationships between groups of variables. They tend to be more complex and minimally annotated compared to presentation visualisations, which are for communicating the final findings to others.

Presentation visualisations are designed to emphasise the findings and insights we want an external audience to understand. We want to highlight as many interesting findings as possible without including so much information that it overwhelms our audience. With so much competition for our attention, it is more important than ever to be able to communicate data effectively and efficiently. The presentation of our information has to be not only engaging, but quickly and easily understood.

The visualisation types differ in four key aspects:

2.1 Who is the data for?

  1. Audience

    The primary audience for data exploration visualisations is you, the data analyst. The analyst is the person who is both manipulating the data and seeing the results. They needs to work in cycles of defining hypotheses, analysing data, and visualizing results.

    Presentation visualisations are not for the author of the analyses, but for a separate group of end-users who are not familiar with the work. These figures appear in reports, journal articles, talks, and media.

2.2 What do you want to say?

  1. Message

    Data exploration is journey to develop insights or find some underlying structure in the data. This is often the first step in an analysis. It is a wandering and iterative path during which the analyst is trying to put together the pieces of a puzzle.

    Presentation figures illustrate the end finding. They are for sharing the solved puzzle with people who can take action on the insights. Authors of data presentations need to guide an audience through the content with a clear purpose and point of view.

Data exploration is a journey to find truth; data presentation should guide your audience to focus on the most important data and insights.

2.3 What do you want to say?

  1. Explanation

    For the analysts making exploratory figures, the meaning of their analysis can be self-evident.

    Effective presentation figures need context. Context could include the data source, the pattern observed, how it relates to other data, etc. When the audience isnât as familiar with the data, the data presentation author needs to start with more basic descriptions and context. This context can be included by figure annotations, a caption, written explanations of the variables, or a short summary highlighting the main points of the visualisation.

2.4 How do you show the data?

  1. Complexity.

    The visualizations for data exploration are often easy to create and may often show multiple dimensions to unearth complex patterns.

    Presentation visualisations are less complex than exploration figures; it is important that they are simple and intuitive enough for the audience to decipher the meaning of a figure. Lower complexity could entail only showing a subset of the data or using fewer variables. Colours used in presentation figures should be distinct, colour blind friendly, and in the case of articles readable when printed in greyscale.

Data exploration visualisations generally display all the information on a single page; data presentation needs better flow and explanation to tell the story properly.
